  <!-- Section 1: What is a VA loan? -->
  <h2 id="what-is-a-va-loan">What Is a VA Loan?</h2>
  <p>
    A VA loan is a mortgage backed by the U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs. Like FHA loans, the VA does not lend money directly — it guarantees a portion of the loan so that private lenders can offer you better terms. The result is one of the most powerful mortgage products available: zero down payment, no private mortgage insurance, and competitive interest rates.
  </p>
  <p>
    VA loans were created as part of the original GI Bill in 1944 to help returning service members buy homes. Today, the benefit extends to veterans, active-duty service members, certain National Guard and Reserve members, and eligible surviving spouses.
  </p>
  <p>
    San Diego's large military community — home to Marine Corps Air Station Miramar, Naval Base San Diego, Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton, and Naval Base Coronado — makes VA loans one of the most commonly used mortgage products in the county. In fact, San Diego consistently ranks as the number one county in the nation for VA loan volume.
  </p>

  <!-- Section 2: Who qualifies? -->
  <h2 id="who-qualifies">Who Qualifies for a VA Loan?</h2>
  <p>
    VA loan eligibility is based on your military service. You must meet one of the following service requirements:
  </p>
  <h3>Service Requirements</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Active duty:</strong> At least 90 consecutive days of active service during wartime, or 181 days during peacetime. If you are currently serving, you need at least 90 continuous days.</li>
    <li><strong>Veterans:</strong> Must have been discharged under conditions other than dishonorable and meet the minimum service length for your era of service.</li>
    <li><strong>National Guard and Reserves:</strong> Six or more years of service in the Selected Reserve or National Guard, or 90 days of active-duty service under Title 10 orders.</li>
    <li><strong>Surviving spouses:</strong> Unremarried surviving spouses of veterans who died in service or from a service-connected disability may be eligible. Remarried surviving spouses may qualify if the remarriage occurred after age 57 and after December 16, 2003.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Certificate of Eligibility (COE)</h3>
  <p>
    To apply for a VA loan, you need a Certificate of Eligibility. This document confirms your service history and entitlement amount. You can request it online through the VA's eBenefits portal, by mail using VA Form 26-1880, or your lender can often pull it electronically during the application process.
  </p>
  <h3>Credit and Income</h3>
  <p>
    The VA does not set a minimum credit score, but most lenders require at least 620. Some lenders in San Diego work with lower scores on a case-by-case basis. You will also need to demonstrate stable income and meet the VA's residual income requirements, which ensure you have enough money left over after all major expenses to cover day-to-day living costs.
  </p>

  <!-- Section 3: VA loan benefits -->
  <h2 id="va-loan-benefits">VA Loan Benefits</h2>
  <p>
    The VA loan is widely considered the best mortgage product available in the United States. Here is why:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>No down payment required.</strong> You can finance 100% of the home's purchase price — even in a high-cost market like San Diego. On a $800,000 home, that means you skip the $28,000 to $160,000 down payment that other loan types would require.</li>
    <li><strong>No private mortgage insurance (PMI).</strong> Conventional and FHA loans both require mortgage insurance when you put less than 20% down. VA loans never charge PMI, which can save you hundreds of dollars per month.</li>
    <li><strong>Competitive interest rates.</strong> Because the VA guaranty reduces lender risk, VA rates are typically among the lowest available. Contact a licensed loan officer for current rate information.</li>
    <li><strong>Limited closing costs.</strong> The VA caps certain closing costs and prohibits lenders from charging specific fees (such as prepayment penalties or attorney fees in some states), reducing your out-of-pocket expenses.</li>
    <li><strong>Easier qualification.</strong> VA underwriting guidelines are generally more flexible on debt-to-income ratios and credit history compared to conventional loans.</li>
    <li><strong>Reusable benefit.</strong> Your VA entitlement is not a one-time benefit. You can use it multiple times throughout your life, as long as you restore your entitlement (typically by selling the previous VA-financed home and paying off the loan).</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- Section 4: VA loan limits in San Diego -->
  <h2 id="va-loan-limits">VA Loan Limits in San Diego</h2>
  <p>
    If you have <strong>full entitlement</strong> — meaning you have never used your VA loan benefit before, or you have restored it after paying off a previous VA loan — there is no loan limit. You can borrow as much as a lender is willing to approve, with no down payment required.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you have <strong>reduced entitlement</strong> — for example, you still have an existing VA loan on another property — the county loan limit comes into play. For San Diego County in 2026, the conforming loan limit is $1,104,000. You can still borrow above that amount, but you may need a down payment to cover the difference between your remaining entitlement and 25% of the loan amount.
  </p>
  <p>
    For most first-time VA buyers in San Diego, full entitlement means you can purchase well into seven figures without putting any money down. This is a significant advantage in a county where median home prices are among the highest in California.
  </p>

  <!-- Section 5: Pros and cons -->
  <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Pros and Cons of VA Loans</h2>
