  <!-- Section 6: VA vs FHA vs Conventional -->
  <h2 id="va-vs-other-loans">VA vs. FHA vs. Conventional Loans</h2>
  <p>
    If you are eligible for a VA loan, it is almost always the best choice. But here is how it stacks up against the alternatives:
  </p>
  <ComparisonTable
    headers={["Feature", "VA", "FHA", "Conventional"]}
    rows={[
      ["Min. down payment", "0%", "3.5%", "3%"],
      ["Mortgage insurance", "None (funding fee instead)", "MIP for life of loan", "PMI until 20% equity"],
      ["Min. credit score", "No VA minimum (lenders: 620+)", "580 (for 3.5% down)", "620+"],
      ["Loan limit (SD)", "No limit (full entitlement)", "$1,077,550", "$1,104,000 (conforming)"],
      ["Funding fee / upfront cost", "2.15% first use (waived if disabled)", "1.75% UFMIP", "None"],
      ["Eligible borrowers", "Military-connected", "Anyone", "Anyone"],
      ["Property restrictions", "Primary residence, VA appraisal", "Primary residence, FHA appraisal", "Most property types"],
    ]}
    caption="Loan type comparison for San Diego (estimates only)"
    highlightColumn={1}
  />
  <p>
    The biggest advantage of VA over FHA is the combination of zero down payment and no ongoing mortgage insurance. Even with the VA funding fee factored in, the total cost of a VA loan is typically thousands of dollars less over the life of the mortgage.
  </p>

  <!-- Section 7: VA funding fee -->
  <h2 id="va-funding-fee">VA Funding Fee Explained</h2>
  <p>
    The VA funding fee is a one-time charge that helps fund the VA loan program so it can continue to serve future veterans. The fee varies based on your service type, down payment, and whether you have used your VA benefit before.
  </p>
  <ComparisonTable
    headers={["Scenario", "Funding Fee"]}
    rows={[
      ["First-time use, 0% down", "2.15%"],
      ["First-time use, 5%+ down", "1.5%"],
      ["First-time use, 10%+ down", "1.25%"],
      ["Subsequent use, 0% down", "3.3%"],
      ["Subsequent use, 5%+ down", "1.5%"],
      ["Subsequent use, 10%+ down", "1.25%"],
    ]}
    caption="2026 VA funding fee rates (estimates only)"
  />
  <p>
    On an $800,000 loan with zero down and first-time use, the funding fee would be approximately $17,200. This amount can be financed into the loan so you do not need to pay it out of pocket at closing.
  </p>
  <h3>Who Is Exempt from the Funding Fee?</h3>
  <p>
    The following groups do not pay a VA funding fee:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Veterans receiving VA disability compensation</li>
    <li>Veterans who would be entitled to disability compensation but receive retirement or active-duty pay instead</li>
    <li>Surviving spouses of veterans who died in service or from a service-connected disability</li>
    <li>Active-duty service members who provide evidence of a Purple Heart (as of 2020)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If you have a service-connected disability rating, the funding fee waiver can save you thousands of dollars and makes the VA loan even more advantageous.
  </p>

  <!-- Section 8: How to apply -->
  <h2 id="how-to-apply">How to Apply for a VA Loan in San Diego</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Obtain your Certificate of Eligibility (COE).</strong> Request it through the VA's eBenefits portal or ask your lender to retrieve it electronically. Active-duty members should request a statement of service from their commanding officer.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Check your credit.</strong> While the VA has no minimum score, most lenders require 620 or higher. Review your credit report for errors and address any issues before applying.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Choose a VA-experienced lender.</strong> Not all lenders are equally experienced with VA loans. In San Diego, look for a lender who processes a high volume of VA transactions — they will be familiar with common appraisal issues, VA-specific underwriting guidelines, and how to handle the funding fee waiver for disabled veterans.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Get pre-approved.</strong> A pre-approval letter shows sellers you are a qualified buyer. In San Diego's competitive market, strong pre-approval can make the difference between winning and losing a bidding situation.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Find your home.</strong> Work with a real estate agent familiar with VA transactions. Some agents specialize in military relocations and PCS moves, which is helpful if you are on a tight timeline.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Complete the VA appraisal.</strong> The VA assigns an independent appraiser to confirm the home's value and verify it meets minimum property requirements. VA appraisals tend to be slightly more detailed than conventional appraisals.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Close on your loan.</strong> Once underwriting is complete, you sign closing documents and receive your keys. Closing typically takes 30 to 45 days.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <!-- Section 9: DPA programs -->
  <h2 id="dpa-programs">Down Payment Assistance Programs That Work with VA Loans</h2>
  <p>
    Since VA loans already offer zero down payment, you might wonder why you would need assistance. The answer: closing costs. Even with a VA loan, you will have closing costs such as the appraisal fee, title insurance, recording fees, and potentially the funding fee. Several local and state programs can help cover these expenses.
  </p>
  <h3>San Diego Housing Commission (SDHC)</h3>
  <p>
    SDHC programs can provide deferred-payment assistance that covers closing costs on a VA loan. Eligibility depends on income and the property's location within the City of San Diego.
  </p>
  <h3>CalHFA Programs</h3>
  <p>
    While CalHFA's first mortgage products are designed for FHA and conventional loans, some of their assistance programs (like ZIP Extra for closing costs) may be compatible with VA financing depending on the lender. Check with a CalHFA-approved lender for current compatibility.
  </p>
  <h3>GSFA Platinum</h3>
  <p>
    GSFA offers closing cost assistance that can pair with VA loans. The assistance is structured as a grant or repayable second, depending on the program tier, and can significantly reduce your out-of-pocket costs at closing.
  </p>
  <p>
    Many military-specific nonprofits also offer closing cost grants to service members buying their first home. Your lender or a local housing counselor can help identify these resources.
  </p>

